Marsha Norman (born September 21, 1947) is an American playwright, screenwriter, and novelist.
Norman was born in Louisville, Kentucky, the oldest of four children of Billie and Bertha Williams.
She later began attending productions by the newly founded Actors Theatre of Louisville.
Norman's first play Getting Out was produced at the Actors Theatre of Louisville and then Off-Broadway in 1979.
It reflects Norman's experience working with disturbed adolescents at Kentucky's Central State Hospital.
Norman's success with Getting Out led her to move to New York City where she continued to write for the Actors Theatre of Louisville.

However, her follow-up play, Traveller in the Dark received scathing reviews from the New York critics, some of whom were as blunt to say she could not have written it.
She was in high demand in Hollywood, though not always for films that she liked, or that studios would approve.
Norman and composer Jason Robert Brown made a symphonic adaptation of the children's novel The Trumpet of the Swan, which premiered at the Kennedy Center in 2008.
